Understood. Here's an example indicator that exits a long position at the current market price:

```
//@version=4
study(title="Exit at Market Price Indicator", overlay=true)

// Set up long entry condition
longCondition = crossover(sma(close, 20), sma(close, 50))

// Enter long position
if (longCondition)
    strategy.entry("Long", strategy.long, comment="Long Entry")

// Exit long position at market price
if (strategy.position_size > 0)
    strategy.close("Long", comment="Exit at Market Price", market=true)
```
In this example, we first set up a long entry condition using a crossover of the 20-period and 50-period simple moving averages.

Then, when the long entry condition is met, we enter a long position using an `if` statement rather than the `strategy.entry` function.

Finally, we use another `if` statement to check if we have a long position open and call the `strategy.close` function to close the long position at market price.

Note that in an indicator, the `strategy` functions don't actually execute trades as they do in a strategy. Instead, they are used to plot trade signal arrows, show trade statistics and alerts.
